@node about "Harlot V1.04; About"

Welcome, Harlot V1.04 is a small hack that I wrote one day when I grew
quite annoyed by having to actively click the mouse on the WB screen to use
any of its menus after I had just played with a CLI.  This program Lends
the Workbench menus to the CLI window that has had Harlot run on it, it
fills that potential that was wasted by the standard shells.

For those that are curious, this program was initially written in assembly,
though for some reason it would only lend to two CLI's, and the code was a
little unweildly, so I rewrote it in C...it should always choose the right
window to lend the menu from and to, but there isn't alot that can be done
to make sure - infact there is only one other way that I can think of to
make sure that we are getting the workbench menu, however, I really can't
be flagged adding the code.

BTW: there is NO attempt to automatically, safely remove the LendMenus(),
as that would at the least require the patch of CloseWindow() and as the
programmers amoung you may know, patches can often be patched away - not
to mention that it would require more work <sigh>
See @{"Command-Line" link commandline} for information on how to manually remove the sharing of
a menu.

Harlot has been tested on the following configurations:

Stock A1200 on WB3.0
Stock A1200 on WB3.1 (specifically 40.3)
A1200 w/ Blizzard 1230 @ 50mzh w/ 9.5meg of RAM, 3.0WB

Here are some observations that I have noticed:
 Under Workbench 3.0 whenever you select @{b}ResetWB@{ub} from the tools menu, it
appears to reallocate the Workbench menus without taking into account
potential LendMenus() that could be attached.  Under 3.1 this appears to
have changed, or the menus are nolonger deallocated and then reallocated.
 @{b}Last Message@{ub} from the Workbench menu appears to not work due to
gathering information from the active window as opposed to the Workbench
window...and as there is no appropriate information for the window, it
displays nothing.

@endnode

@node commandline "Harlot V1.04; Commandline"

The main reason for the creation of Harlot V1.04 was to implement the
commandline so that Harlot could be deactivated.  To deactivate from a
shell that has an active Harlot running type:
 Harlot r
Make sure that it is a lowercase 'r' aswell!
 Running harlot without a "r" or infact, anything other than a single "r"
shall invoke LendMenus();

A friend of mine suggested that people put it in their shell-startup so
that it would automagically attach the menus whenever a shell is run.

@endnode

@node warning "Harlot V1.04; WARNING!"

Harlot is a HACK, it is concievable that this program will only work
stably on MY computer, if it does, well, tough...As this program is a hack
it can crash, cause enforcer hits, break all the rules, and it doesn't even
have to be politically correct...so it could be totally unstable on your
system...so keep that in mind.
  I, after testing it for a short while have not found any problems...
 If you do have any problems with the program crashing, give me a yell...

 One last thing, DO NOT run this program when workbench is unavailable!

@endnode

